When printing for some time the motors get hot.
I do not like that.
I looked at some designs for fans mounted to the motors, but they only did the X and Y motor.
With this solution you can do the X-,Y- and Z- Axis and bring the heat outside of the printing area

Find some old laptops and remove the heatpipes
I used 2 old broken HP nc6120 and one broken HP nc 6320 because they have copper heatpipes. Because of the available screws I had to widen one of the holes.
Furtermore I have bent a small ridge outwards. The right hand side motor is the most easy.
Drill a small hole in the frame for the right screw and a larger one for the screw on the left.
The fit is good and the heat gets transported outside of the frame.
(I have added some distance blocks to protect the heatpipe) The left hand side is more complicated. The headpipe needs to be bent to avoid blocking access to some switch screws.
The connection to the motor is also less than with the right hand side motor.
This can be fixed by using the paste that is used with ICs The Z-axis motor is very comparable to the right hand side motor.
Fixed with just 2 screws.

This thing was made with Tinkercad. 8-ball bearings. Noodling around. A well-tuned and precise printer might just make this work. Can't test until I get my Printrbot, but might benefit from more bearings, larger diameter, scaling up. The individual balls just kiss the races inside and out. This design might also benefit from some kind of bearing holder. You can order one here: http://www.shapeways.com/shops/bitforge Check out the "Improved Ball Bearings" for greater precision and maybe even functionality.

I am not sure how round the bearings in this Thing will come out. When you print it, let me know.
Thanks!



I had a couple of these printed up by Shapeways, and as a bearing, they are terrible. The precision of the printing process used is such that the bearings are fused to the inner and outer races. If you could break them free (and I haven't), they would be a lumpy, dumpy bearing that would soon self-destruct. I think a better plan of action is to print the inner and outer races, adjusting for the precision of your printer, and use off the shelf round things for bearings (BBs, pellets, airsoft, etc). Keep me posted, Thingmakers.

The Thing allows someone to create a stackable PS3 system, or any other game system that isless than 3.5" tall. This will allow you to stack another stereo/video component on top of the PS3.
I included both files to print support feet and either a single or dual brackets. The brackets will fit within any build area that is the same as a Makerbot 2 or larger.
This is a design of my own. Feel free to modify and share it. but please give me credit for the original design.
Cheers.

Recommended print settings for PLA are as follows:
25% to 30% infill
50 to 100 mm/s feedrate
100 to 130 travelrate
180 F (Follow the temps you found that work best for the PLA that you are using.)
Print either 1 or 2 brackets. 2 are needed to support anything with any weight. The bracket are positioned on the side and are 145mm tall. They can be printed with or without rafting. No support material is needed.
2 sets of the feet need to be printed (1 set per bracket). 6 feet are required for each bracket (1 set). 12 feet are required for both brackets (2 sets).
Recommended material for the feet:
NinjaFlex TPE. Any color.
Feet will hold inside the bracket with their own pressure if you print the files without resizing.
Enjoy.

remixed_from.title: Reinforced Prusa X Carriage with Slim LM8UU Holder

title: Prusa X Carriage with integrated Z Probe and Fan Holder

description.text:
A new x carriage for prusa style printers (rod distance 50mm) with integrated z probe and fan holder. The arm of the retractable probe is designed to press against the carriage so the probe does not change its z position over time.
The carriage runs on 4 lm8uu bearings which are ziptied for easy removal. A 40mm fan can be attached on one side. A retractable z probe (just a 9g servo and a microswitch required) fixes all your bed leveling problems. On the back side the carriage has the same mount for an extension as the original carriage made by jonaskuehling.
Your hotend needs to be long enough to print without the fan holder touching the build plate and short enough not to crash while z probing. I have a hexagon hotend mounted with the supplied aluminum bracket on top of the carriage.
The z probe has completely eliminated the need for any kind of z calibration since it is properly set up. Now it is just a button press to print.
There is still a minor issue present in the current design. The servo motor is held only by a single screw and tends to wobble around a bit, but as the arm is pressed against the carriage the probing precision is still really good.

Print: .2 or .3 layers are fine, infill can be about 50%
Assemble:
  • Attach the servo with the rotational axis facing away from the carriage.
  • Glue the servo horn on the arm and fix the probing switch (hint: use a decent quality switch, my first version used an old one from the parts bin and it was not precise enough, I now use one from cherry and am very satisfied with the performance).
  • Attach the arm to the servo such that the range of motion is big enough to cover probing and parking position.
  • Fix the lm8uu bearings with zipties.
  • Mount the fan on the bracket.
  • Mount your hotend/extruder.
    Firmware setup: I used this guide here: http://goo.gl/e9gmFi to set up.

description.text: A simple over-arm type clamp that I am using to hold down a portable gas canister- I'm sure it has lots of other uses. Clamps 60-70mm dia objects. Mine are made from 6mm MDF

To build each clamp youâ€™ll need the following plastic/wood parts: 1x Gas_canister_mounting_bracket_LH
1x Gas_canister_mounting_bracket_RH
1x Gas_canister_mounting_bracket_overarm You'll also need:
2x M4x12 hex head bolts (or equiv.)
2x M6x20 hex head bolts (+2x for mounting, length to suit)
2x M6 nuts (or use 1x wing nut + 1x normal) (+ 2x for mounting)
4x 6mm Washers Build as follows:

  • Assemble each of the handed sides together (1x LH and 1x RH) using the short M4 bolts (if using MDF there is no need to cut threads into the parts).

  • Push the over-arm ends into the cavities in the assembled bracket base. It will only fit one way (it may fit the other way, but it wont work).

  • Fit 1x M6 bolt along with its washers and nut to act as the hinge

  • Fit the other bolt/washers/nut to the other end

  • Thatâ€™s it, Done. You should be able to rotate the over-arm piece about 15 degrees (from one end of the slot to the other)
    • Repeat the process to make as many as you need. To grip an object just close the over-arm and tighten the non-hinge nut/bolt. To mount, youâ€™ll need two 6mm holes coincident with the channels in the clamp body. Iâ€™ve included the source files to allow you scale to suit other items. The item shown will clamp about 60mm -70 mm diameter. If I've missed anything, let me know. That's it. Enjoy.

description.text: This is another spider coupler I designed to eliminate "z wobble" (and for me a slightly bent threaded rod). Unlike similar designs, I found plastic & rubber spacers slightly  rigid. I have included a mold to fill with a substance of your choice (i used bathroom silicone). Although the silicone is soft, I have tested z travel with a dial gauge and its spot on. I don't have the hardware sizes I used (sorry), but it is the standard Printrbot shipped hardware. I left the tolerances a little tight so it will require some cleaning.

I printed the parts as follows: -2x bottom coupler @ 90% infill .35mm layer height (.35 is my minimum .50 will work fine)
-2x top coupler @ 90% infill .35mm layer height I used honeycomb support (my bridging is horrible at the moment)
-2x molds @90 % infill .4mm layer height -Once you have all your parts printed fill your molds, level off with a credit card etc... and allow to dry (mine took a good 24hr for silicone to cure) -Clean as necessary, you will need re-drill out some holes. You will need a small nut and bolt for each of the bottom couplers, and a large nut for each threaded rod (top coupler). The small nuts will fit in the bottom couplers very snug, some cleaning of the first layer is required before it will fin in. -I made sure the nuts went into the top coupler very snug, then threaded rod with several layers of Teflon tape. (to prevent the threaded rod from slipping, you may want to tighten with tools) -Finally I broke the thin walls off the mold and was able to slide it out easily. You may want to double check the center mass of the spacer (if you use silicone) as mine was still uncured in the middle. -Assemble & enjoy P.S...... I applied acetone to the outer layer with a syringe (especially the teeth) to strengthen it.

comments.text: If your total resistance is at 6-5 ohms then you should get 2 to 2.4 ohms.  Voltage divided by resistance will give you amps.  I have 2- 12 ohm 5 watt resisters in parallel  that divides the resistance and gives me a total resistance of 6 ohms.  That gets me about 2 amps and it heats really well. I suppose if you want more heat then drop your resistance down and you will get more amps/power.  Be careful not to over drive the hotend power transistor on the board. let me know if that helps.
comments.author: whosawhatsis

comments.text: As I suspected, you're not running a 10W heater. You're running a 24W heater. W = V * A, so if you have 2A on a 12V source, that's 24W. The wattage rating on the resistor doesn't tell you how many watts you'll get through it, it tells you how much wattage it is designed to dissipate as heat. You are running the resistors at 2.4x their rating, and if not for the aluminum block to carry the heat away, they would burn out.

description.text:
A small (~80mmx80mm) print of the Valles Marinaris region on Mars. You can make your own (if you aren't afraid of the terminal) by using png23d and freeware like MeshLab. png23d takes a greyscale image (like the one I posted, which shows actual topographic data from the MOLA instrument) and assigns different heights based on the pixel greyscale value. Porting the resultant solid to MeshLab allows you to reduce the number of facets to something more reasonable (like 100,000). I'm still working on the process in my spare time and haven't quite worked out the bugs...
I didn't generate this stl - I found it at this site: http://nasa3d.arc.nasa.gov/detail/valles-marineris
From the nasa website:
"This STL file is a topographic model of a portion of Valles Marineris with vertical exageration, derived from data collected by the MOLA altimeter onboard NASA's Mars Global Surveyor mission. Printed at its default size (8cm across) this model cover an area approximately 1000km across at a scale of 12.5 million to one ( 1 cm = 125 km ) Data Credit : NASA/MOLA Science Team"
Because I snagged the stl file from a NASA site, I'm giving this a Public Domain Dedication. If that makes anyone unhappy, please let me know. Keep in mind I'm just posting this to Thingiverse after trying it out! All the credit for making it is NASA's.
The Gale Crater thing I cited as an inspiration was created in this fashion.

I layered mine with orange and black to mimic the rusty color of Mars. Didn't quite work the way I had planned, but I do like the striped look. I've found that printing in a mono-chrome makes it difficult to distinguish surface features.
I printed without a raft and switched from the natural filament (used because it's so cheap) to orange after the first 'ceiling' layer at the bottom of the canyon was laid down. I then changed the filament every 10 min or so, using the 'Change Filament' routine on the Replicator 2. The orange takes a few layers to really get a nice color down, especially on top of the black, but I like the look.

This is a design I put together for a medieval plaque belt. The design may not be widely interesting, but I think the technique is useful.
Basically I designed an individual plaque in Sketchup, printed it, then made a rubber mold from the print and cast a bunch of pewter plaques from the mold.

If there is interest, I can go into more detail on pewter casting from 3D prints, but a quick search of Instructables.com is probably enough. I love this combination of techniques: 3d CAD, 3d printing, rubber molding, and pewter casting. It allows a guy like[ me who can't draw a straight line to produce art I am proud of.

I took MNinventers nice Train design that was published Dec 26, 2011 and splitted it into parts for printing without support using Sketchup Make. All fixed with netfabb cloud service and test printed. I also wanted the wheels to be able to turn, making it a toy.

Print the pieces from the colors and in amount that is given in the file names and glue them together in the end. I didn't use any support at all. I printed the main top part three times to get it perfect and ended up combining back roof and the tiny parts on it.
There are two variants of the design. The first uses the main top body with roof. So only print 00 piece for that and skip parts 01 - 04. I used 0.08 mm layers to make the surface smooth, 20% infill and 2 loops should be enough.
For the second one I removed the roof and the tiny parts on it. Print parts 01 - 04 for it.
Then print parts 05 - 17 for both variants. Print at least the 08 axis with 40-60% infill to make them enough stable not to break.
You can print the blank plates piece 18 and combine them with your own words or signs. I printed them black letters/numbers on red plates using the Print on Object plugin in Cura.

  • Allows one-handed dispensing of liquids a drop at a time.
  • Press the round plate to dispense. Press harder for more drops.
  • Great for dispensing alcohol onto swabs or swatches for cleaning small items.
  • A time-saver for polishing gemstones when each facet must be cleaned for inspection during the polishing process.
  • Created with FreeCAD. Example printed in PLA on an Orion Delta printer.

• If printed in PLA, parts can be glued together with gel superglue or Plastruct Weld.
  • The long pusher arm has a nub on one side that presses against the bottle. The round pusher plate should be glued to that same side of the pusher arm.
  • You might want to use a file in-between the two cylindrical posts on the base plate, to smooth them somewhat so that the pusher arm will slide against them easily.
  • The bottle is inserted from the top, through the large ring, then through the small ring.
  • Use foam tape to attach the dispenser to a vertical surface.
  • A few drops will leak out when bottle is first inverted and inserted into the dispenser, but air pressure will soon stop that.
  • The occasional drip can be caught by placing your small bowl of swabs/swatches just below the dispenser.

title: Air-Powered Rocket
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text: This rocket slips onto a 1" PVC pipe, to be fired by compressed air. Our best launch was 306 feet. http://www.youtube.com/watch?feature=player_detailpage&v=TydK261hhFI#t=26s

I printed it with .3 mm layer, 4 extra shells, 30 mm/sec. You might need to experiment a little bit to see what works best for you. The tip is a "solid" hemisphere, its solidity determined by your infill %. I used 40% infill and it seemed to work well enough. For the compressed air tank, we used 3" ABS pipe and end-caps. We inserted a valve stem from a bicycle inner tube, and a threaded sprinkler nipple into holes on one of the end-caps, and filled the gap between the inserts and the holes with gasket adhesive. The pieces were then also hot glued for extra security. Once completed, the end caps were ABS-glued to the pipe. We used an automatic sprinkler valve to release the air. We wired up a 9 volt battery to a big switch to make the launch button. It turns out the sprinkler valve seizes at 70 psi, so we did mot of our launches at 60 psi. We were generally getting between 240 and 280 feet. ** WARNING:
** Please wear hearing protection
 Do not shoot at people, animals or objects
Do not get in front of the launcher
 Make sure everything is secure
*** Test at lower pressures first before working up to higher pressures

description.text:
Create knobs and pulls for your cabinet doors or dresser drawers with this Customizer Thing.
From curved or straight stems, to myriad ornament types (including none), to special indent effects, to cool chamfered (angled) edges, and of course various sizes, you can now create knobs to your hearts' content.

NOTE: There is a bug in Customizer if you use the "curved" stem style. It works fine in OpenSCAD if you download the script and run it locally, but otherwise use the "straight" stem style.
There are two things you'll need to measure -- the diameter (width) of the screw you want to use to hold the knob to the door, and how far out in front of the door the screw extends. All other parameters are up to you.
The script will attempt to keep bad things from happening -- nothing will be un-printable. However, you will most likely need to let your slicing software create support structures, or in some cases, just print with the ornament's flat-side down.

description.text: This is a scale model of the Engineering Cairn (http://www.ubcengineers.ca/about/tradition/the-cairn/) on the University of British Columbia's campus. In order to save on material (and so that the model can double as a 'drinking' glass) the interior is hollow. It has a capacity of 1.5 ounces.

I would highly recommend printing this with ABS or Taulman's 618 Nylon, as PLA's lower glass-transition temperature (60-65 degrees C) will easily be reached during a dishwasher cycle.  
Print with the smallest side up, the internal overhang angles are small enough to not need any supports.  If you are printing with a raft, use a heatgun on the underside where the raft detaches.  This will get rid of the lighter-coloured "stressed" plastic and help make the part water-tight.  
I would like to stress that although this part functions as a beverage container, don't use it as one unless you have considered the safety of using 3D-printed foodware.  The common plastics used in printing, ABS and PLA, have certain grades that are considered foodsafe. HOWEVER, running ANY form of plastic through a 3D printer will introduce oils and other volatiles into the plastic.  In addition, the cavities within a printed part (even one with 100% infill) will never be fully cleaned (by hand or in a dishwasher).  
It boils down to this: use this to hold beverages if you have considered the risks and judged them worth it.
